Forecasting Residential Solar Production and ROI Across U.S. Regions
Team 67
Benjamin Martinez, Coleman Treadwell, Elizabeth Haenel, 
Erin Sinah Cho, Shu Hang Leung, Tan Nguyen
I.	Project Overview
With the price of energy on the rise, many homeowners are making the switch to solar. However, given the complexity of estimating solar irradiance over time along with the comparison of different solar panel technologies and installation costs, it can become a very challenging decision. As adoption grows, there is an increasing need for tools to help facilitate that decision-making. Accurate predictions of solar irradiance can be a crucial input into the cost-benefit analysis that many homeowners are now faced with when considering solar panels. More accurate production forecasts mean more realistic projections of cost savings, payback periods, and financing decisions. 
We plan to build a tool that forecasts and visualizes solar production across regions of the United States to help homeowners better estimate the potential return on investment of installing solar panels on their home. This analysis will leverage publicly available solar irradiance data from the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) to estimate the amount of photovoltaic (PV) energy a home in a given area could be expected to produce. We will pair that data with cost benchmarks from NREL and the National Laboratory of the Rockies (NLR) to estimate a return on investment (ROI) and expected breakeven point. By combining these two analyses with interactive visualization, the tool will help users quickly assess the feasibility and long-term financial value of installing residential rooftop solar panels.

II.	Literature Review
Recent work on solar irradiance forecasting provides the modeling basis for our tool: optimized Artificial Neural Network (ANN) ensembles (Al‑Dahidi et al. 2019), hybrid and recurrent–shallow neural models (Almarzooqi et al. 2024; Castillo‑Rojas, Medina Quispe, and Hernández 2023), and multi‑model or climate‑specific comparisons (Ali et al. 2025; Nguyen et al. 2025; Vanlalchhuanawmi et al. 2025; Zazoum 2022) consistently improve short‑term prediction accuracy and guide algorithm selection, though all depend on consistent weather inputs and risk overfitting across regions. Satellite‑image and cloud‑impact methods (Jang et al. 2016; Fennane et al. 2025) help capture rapid sky changes but require heavier data and computation. To translate forecasts into homeowner‑relevant outputs, PV performance models—Clack’s irradiance‑to‑power regression (2017) and the PVWatts framework (Dobos 2014)—offer validated ways to estimate production and losses, while studies on bifacial mismatch, temperature behavior, cloudy‑day loss separation, and predictive maintenance (Deline et al. 2019; Dong et al. 2025; Qader and Albalooshi 2025; Dinita et al. 2025; Vichare and Gaikwad 2025) refine assumptions about degradation and reliability, even if many focus on utility‑scale or experimental systems. Additional literature on adoption behavior (Sultan et al. 2016) and anomaly detection (Qader and Albalooshi 2025) supports user‑experience and edge‑case considerations. Together, these works justify our approach of benchmarking modern ML models on standardized NREL data, coupling them with PVWatts‑style production and cost modeling, and improving prior studies by integrating uncertainty and tailoring assumptions to residential rooftops.
III.	Methodology And Expected Innovations
A.	Expected Innovations
Our approach expands existing technologies b processing large-scale solar irradiance data from the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) to compute not just energy production, but complex financial estimates like ROI. We will develop an interactive visualization using Leaflet and OpenStreetMap to display a national irradiance heatmap. Users can interact with the map to select a specific location, which will trigger the algorithm to compute estimated energy production and generate a financial burndown plot, dynamically visualizing net savings and payback periods over time.

B.	Measuring Success
If successful, this project will give homeowners an accurate, transparent way to evaluate residential solar feasibility by combining regional irradiance forecasts with cost benchmarks, reducing uncertainty around long-term payback periods. Progress will be evaluated at two checkpoints: the midterm milestone will confirm that the data pipeline, baseline forecasting model, and ROI framework function with early accuracy metrics, while the final checkpoint will validate the completed system by assessing solar production forecasts across multiple regions, comparing ROI estimates with published benchmarks, and ensuring the visualization tool clearly communicates outcomes. Overall effectiveness will be measured through predictive accuracy (MSE, MAE, MAPE) and the tool’s ability to provide homeowners with a clear assessment of residential solar feasibility.

C.	Risk, payoffs and cost
Using public NREL irradiance data eliminates data acquisition costs while providing a massive, reliable foundation for our models. Key risks include modeling assumptions about roof conditions, electricity rate growth, and policy incentives, which may affect ROI accuracy. Project costs are strictly the time and computational resources required for data processing, model training, and interface development. The payoff is a scalable tool that supports homeowner decision-making and can inform broader energy investment and planning.

